title: For Sale:  S&W 645 .45 ACP
postcontent:
Good+++ to Very Good condition Smith and Wesson 645 second-generation, stainless-steel semi-automatic .45ACP pistol.  These are widely considered to be one of the finest pistols ever made and are often described as "built like a tank" and "lasts forever" -- supposedly these are one of the few pistols you will find that can feed EMPTY CASES- this is that reliable of a firearm.  
Please don't simply go by the picture -- it's VERY HARD to get a great pic of this fine firearm... The thing is, if you use the flash, you can wind up with a blurry pic or a pic that's shiny in some areas and off-colored in other areas- almost too vivid, and little bits of light, shadow, shine, etc. can look like imperfections or problems in the gun..  If you DON'T use the flash, it looks like it's faded or terrible condition or 100 years old.  I did the best I could with my smartphone but it's a great looking gun.  I'm told you could use Mother's car polish (or other Mother's products, like the Mag Wheels product or super shine stuff) to polish this up to a parade gloss.This is an amazing firearm -- it's damn nice and amazingly accurate - really impressive for a .45 ACP 30-year-old autoloader.  This is a traditional Smith and Wesson action that is DA/SA - double action with a Decocker/safety lever.  I added brand-new Hogue hardwood grips for nearly $75+ bucks.  These go for $700 all day long regardless of condition, I just want the $650 I spent on it (and I'll take the hit I spent on the $75 grips) ... I am consolidating calibers.   The serial # indicates it was made in 1986.  These are widely considered not only perhaps the finest firearm Smith and Wesson ever made, (with the time-era this was produced coinciding with the golden age of Smith and Wesson's semi-auto production, the best of the best they made) but some of the finest firearms you could own and carry.      The stainless-alloy steel that Smith and Wesson used in the production of the 645s were hardened to absolutely ridiculous levels that near tool-steel hardness ratings.  These are not just built to last, they are quite literally BUILT TO LAST.

postcontent: I have a Smith & Wesson Model 13-1 for sale. I rate this revolver at 96, very slight turn line and minimal muzzle wear. The bluing is fantastic. S&W did not make a Model 13. It is a 4 inch blue, numbered original box, numbered original grips, and labeled to the gun. This is a very tough revolver to find and was the first Model 13 ever made. The reason they made these revolvers was for law enforcement, the New York State Police used the Model 10-6, barreled for 357 magnum, so the Model 13-1 was made immediately after the Model 10-6 and the first production of them went to law enforcement. Also unique is the fixed rear site. The SN dates this revolver to 1976.Shipping FFL to FFL, add $35.

title: For Sale:  SKS Rifle  Sino-Soviet
postcontent: Selling my SKS rifle.  Excellent operating condition and good visual condition.  Lots of photos I can send.As best as I can tell this is an early Sino-Soviet (5 digit arabic serial numbers match the early Sino-Soviet sequences -- perhaps one of the very first as it does not have the proof mark of Factory 26 which I understand the proof tooling came after the factory was up and running and after some rifles were shipped)No import markingsEarly Chinese SKS had a blade bayonet that was changed to a spike sometime in the early 1960sSino-Soviets are preferred by collectors because the Soviets shipped all of the original tooling to the Chinese and were there to do setup, QC, and initial oversight of the factory operations.  Basically, they are both interesting from a historical perspective and have some of the highest quality of the various SKSs.$25 shipping to any FFL.  Happy to send to C&R FFL holders.
